               <p>JONAS TAYLOR. I am <rs id="t18180909-143-viclabel782" type="occupation">coachman</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18180909-143-victim1152 t18180909-143-viclabel782"></join> to Mrs. 
               <persName id="t18180909-143-person1153">
                  Mary 
                  Hodgson
               <interp inst="t18180909-143-person1153" type="surname" value="Hodgson"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18180909-143-person1153" type="given" value="Mary"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18180909-143-person1153" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            , widow. On the 3d of July, about seven o'clock in the evening, I put my coat in the carriage box, in the stable-yard, next morning at seven I missed it. There is no door to the coach-house.</p>

               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18180909-143-person1154">
                  SAMUEL 
                  WALTERS
               <interp inst="t18180909-143-person1154" type="surname" value="WALTERS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18180909-143-person1154" type="given" value="SAMUEL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18180909-143-person1154" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am watchman of Piccadilly. On the 6th of July I saw the prisoner offering the coat for sale for four guineas, in the street; I asked him how he got it? he said his uncle sent it to him from Lincolnshire. I took him into custody.</p>
               <p>(Property produced and sworn to.)</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18180909-143-person1155">
                  JAMES 
                  BLAND
